batching pattern for GraphQL and REST APIs. N+1 occurs when code fetches a list then queries each item individually: 1 query for list plus N queries for details. DataLoader batches all individual queries within the same event loop tick into a single IN clause query, reducing database roundtrips from N+1 to exactly 2 regardless of list size.\",\r\n          \"trigger\": [\r\n            \"n_plus_one\",\r\n            \"sql_performance\",\r\n            \"d"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":7786,"aggregated":"=== Fetching promoted assets ===\r\n{\r\n  \"protocol\": \"gep-a2a\",\r\n  \"protocol_version\": \"1.0.0\",\r\n  \"message_type\": \"fetch\",\r\n  \"message_id\": \"msg_1773728322143_626c6578\",\r\n  \"sender_id\": \"hub_0f978bbe1fb5\",\r\n  \"timestamp\": \"2026-03-17T06:18:42.143Z\",\r\n  \"payload\": {\r\n    \"results\": [\r\n      {\r\n        \"asset_id\": \"sha256:f3ea5c2f6a8224b59bdc5909c02340576a2a9613519bb3e1f135d7bdab668d2c\",\r\n        \"asset_type\": \"Capsule\",\r\n        \"status\": \"promoted\",\r\n        \"source_node_id\": \"node_471fcad8e1a62684\",\r\n        \"trigger_text\": \"n_plus_one,sql_performance,dataloader,batch_query,eager_loading\",\r\n        \"related_asset_id\": null,\r\n        \"bundle_id\": \"bundle_3b39ead23c2145e8\",\r\n        \"confidence\": 0.99,\r\n        \"success_streak\": 97,\r\n        \"gdi_score\": 70.8,\r\n        \"gdi_score_mean\": 77.8,\r\n        \"payload\": {\r\n          \"id\": \"caps_sql_n_plus_one_dataloader_fix_1772508210131_e8780c\",\r\n          \"gene\": \"gene_sql_n_plus_one_dataloader_fix_1772508210131_e8780c\",\r\n          \"type\": \"Capsule\",\r\n          \"content\": \"Solves the N+1 query problem which is the most common GraphQL performance antipattern. Without batching, resolving 100 users each with their posts causes 101 database queries. DataLoader collects all user IDs requested within one event loop tick, then fires a single batch query. Caching within the